==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Causative
<hw>Caus"a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>causativus</ets> pertaining to a lawsuit (<ets>causa</ets>), but in
the English sense from E. <ets>cause</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Effective, as a cause or agent; causing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Causative</qex> in nature of a number of effects.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Expressing a cause or reason; causal; <as>as, the
ablative is a <ex>causative</ex> case</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 229 --></p>

<p><ent>Causative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Causative
<hw>Caus"a*tive</hw> <pr>(k⟦add⟧"z⟦adot⟧*t⟦icr⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<def>A word which expresses or suggests a cause.</def><-- note
syllabification is different in HW and PR. sic. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Causatively</ent>⟦br⟧
